{"cursor":"40157","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nA 'palindrome' is a word, phrase, number, or other sequence of symbols or\nelements, whose meaning may be interpreted the same way in either forward or\nreverse direction. with general allowances for adjustments to punctuation\nand word dividers.\n\nComposing literature in palindromes is an example of constrained writing. The\nword \"palindrome\" was coined from the Greek roots {{lang|grc-Latn|palin}} (;\n\"again\") and {{lang|grc-Latn|dromos}} (; \"way, direction\") by the English writer\nBen Jonson in the 17th century. The Greek phrase to describe the phenomenon is\n{{lang|grc-Latn|karkinikÃª epigrafÃª}} (; \"crab inscription\"), or simply karkinoi\n(; \"crabs\"), alluding to the movement of crabs, such as an inscription that may\nbe read backwards.\n","linknr":623,"url":"Palindromic","recorded":1362561192,"links":72,"instances":["band","simpson","music","album","the_stone_roses_song","music","letter","abba_song","literature","biology","band","mathematics","poet","music","simpson","band","film","simpson","poet","fruit","webern","composer","composer","haydn","album","letter","music","song"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Constrained writing","Palindromes|","Word games"],"headings":["History","Types","Long palindromes","Biological structures","Computation theory","Semordnilap","Non-English palindromes","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Sator_Square_at_Opp%C3%A8de.jpg/220px-Sator_Square_at_Opp%C3%A8de.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/1/f/31f286cf5d943a535f79e9ca4408ff3f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/b/8/7b8b965ad4bca0e41ab51de7b31363a1.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/DNA_palindrome.svg/600px-DNA_palindrome.svg.png","//bit